## Truth hierarchy

When sources disagree, the higher one wins:

1. Code in `src/**`
2. CI in `.github/workflows/**`
3. [`.github/CODEOWNERS`](mdc:.github/CODEOWNERS)
4. [docs/ai/**](mdc:docs/ai/README.md)
5. [AGENTS.md](mdc:AGENTS.md)
6. Tool-specific layers (this file, `CLAUDE.md`, `copilot-instructions.md`)

## Non-negotiables (every change)

- **Idiomatic.** Match surrounding code, not your training.
- **Atomic.** One logical change per PR. No drive-by edits.
- **Reusable.** Search before creating a new component / util / constant /
  shared type. See [docs/ai/frontend/reusability.md](mdc:docs/ai/frontend/reusability.md).
- **Typed.** No `any`, no `as unknown as …`, no suppressed `svelte-check`
  warnings. In Rust: no `unwrap()` / `expect()` in non-test code.
- **i18n + a11y (FE).** No hard-coded English. No bare clickable `<div>`.
  See [docs/ai/frontend/i18n-and-a11y.md](mdc:docs/ai/frontend/i18n-and-a11y.md).
- **CI green locally.** `npm run format && npm run lint -- --max-warnings 0
  && npm run check && npm run test` before any FE PR. For Rust changes, also
  `./scripts/lint.rust.sh && ./scripts/lint.did.sh`. See
  [docs/ai/pr-and-ci.md](mdc:docs/ai/pr-and-ci.md).
- **Conventional PR title.** `verb(scope): description`. CI enforces it.
- **No Jira / Atlassian links** in PR descriptions — CI rejects them.

## Meta-update rule

If your change introduces a new pattern, shared component, naming
convention, shared type, or workflow — update the corresponding page in
`docs/ai/**` in the **same PR**. See
[docs/ai/governance.md#meta-update-rule](mdc:docs/ai/governance.md).
